-- Alltel net profit falls after wireline spin-off
-- 
-- Tue Feb 20, 2007 10:20am EST
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/02/20/us-alltel-results-idUSN2047513020070220

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - Alltel Corp. ( AT.N ) on Tuesday posted better-than-expected profit and revenue as the rural wireless provider attracted new subscribers, and shares rose more than 2 percent in early trading. 


 The company also forecast a rise in service revenues in 2007. Alltel, which spun off its wireline business last year to form Windstream Corp., said fourth-quarter net income fell to $216 million, or 58 cents per share, from $255 million, or 66 cents a share, a year earlier. Earnings per share from current businesses was 63 cents, up from 40 cents per share a year earlier and beating the average Wall Street estimate of 59 cents, according to Reuters Estimates. The company, based in Little Rock, Arkansas, said revenue rose 14 percent to $2.09 billion, compared to the average analyst forecast of $2.07 billion according to Reuters Estimates. Alltel Corp. ( AT.N ) ( AT.N ) Chief Financial Officer Sharilyn Gasaway said on Tuesday that she expects the wireless carrier to report 2007 service revenue of $7.8 billion to $8 billion. The company reported service revenue of $7.0 billion in 2006. She also forecast 2007 OIBDA, or operating income before depreciation and amortization, of $2.9 billion to $3 billion, up about 11 to 15 percent from its 2006 wireless OIBDA. She also said that she expects the company to have capital expenditures of $1.15 billion to $1.25 billion during 2007. The shares rose $1.48 or 2.45 percent to $61.91. Alltel said it added 228,000 net customers in the quarter, up 55 percent from a year ago and ending 2006 with nearly 12 million customers. Customer cancellations, known as churn, was 1.92 percent in the fourth quarter.